to mention the results.

28:05.518 --> 28:08.180
Instead they go on about the lung resection.

28:08.271 --> 28:12.480
Which they performed
because of "structural alterations."

28:13.901 --> 28:16.643
What are "structural alterations"?

28:17.154 --> 28:19.861
It's what doctors say
when they're trying to avoid using the word

28:19.949 --> 28:22.440
that it almost inevitably describes.

28:25.621 --> 28:27.077
Who is this man?

28:27.164 --> 28:28.153
(DOOR SHUTS)

28:35.548 --> 28:36.788
Just a little.

28:39.218 --> 28:40.799
One doesn't want to overdo it.

28:41.971 --> 28:44.087
One doesn't want to look ill, either.

28:45.224 --> 28:46.600
A sick...

28:46.684 --> 28:49.221
(STUTTERING)

28:49.312 --> 28:51.223
...king is no good to anyone.

28:52.106 --> 28:53.095
(CLEARS THROAT)

28:54.400 --> 28:55.901
There must be no weakness.

28:57.278 --> 28:59.189
No vulnerability.

29:03.159 --> 29:04.490
Oh, thank you.

29:09.332 --> 29:10.321
(SIGHS)

29:16.047 --> 29:17.082
Evening Chronicle!

29:17.173 --> 29:19.414
(OVERLAPPING CONVERSATIONS)

29:28.309 --> 29:30.345
(APPLAUSE)

29:37.526 --> 29:40.017
-What's that?
-An armchair, sir.

29:40.446 --> 29:42.437
Ijust thought, a man of his age...

29:42.531 --> 29:44.522
This one never sits. Get rid of it.

29:46.702 --> 29:48.442
Mr. Churchill, Your Majesty.

29:54.043 --> 29:55.249
Your Majesty.

29:56.879 --> 29:58.335
The people have spoken.

29:58.965 --> 30:02.002
Your party has won the election,

30:03.219 --> 30:06.882
and as... As their Sovereign,

30:06.973 --> 30:10.181
I invite you to form a government
in my name.

30:10.267 --> 30:12.644
An honor I gratefully accept.

30:13.312 --> 30:16.896
My dear Winston, congratulations.

30:17.650 --> 30:22.815
Would it be terribly unconstitutional of me
to say how happy I am?

30:24.991 --> 30:27.448
I've missed our weekly chats.

30:28.160 --> 30:30.242
(CLEARS THROAT)

30:31.706 --> 30:35.415
Your predecessor is a fine parliamentarian.

30:36.627 --> 30:37.707
A good man.

30:37.795 --> 30:40.332
But, um, well,

30:40.423 --> 30:43.506
as company, as a companion...

30:44.093 --> 30:45.082
(SIGHS)

30:45.177 --> 30:47.589
An empty taxi pulled up
at the House of Commons,

30:47.680 --> 30:49.011
and Mr. Attlee got out?

30:49.098 --> 30:51.339
(LAUGHS AND COUGHS)

30:51.434 --> 30:52.640
Quite.

30:52.727 --> 30:53.716
(COUGHS)

30:54.478 --> 30:55.513
(SIGHS)

30:55.604 --> 30:58.346
Now you may congratulate me in return.

30:58.691 --> 31:00.773
Uh... Wha... What for?

31:01.402 --> 31:02.892
My rapid recovery.

31:03.612 --> 31:04.988
Oh. (CHUCKLES)

31:05.072 --> 31:06.278
Yes.

31:06.866 --> 31:10.450
I seem to have bounced back
a lot quicker than people expected.

31:11.162 --> 31:12.277
Yes.

31:13.039 --> 31:17.624
Not sure I ever imagined what breathing
through one lung would feel like.

31:18.711 --> 31:21.544
Turns out there's barely
any difference. (CHUCKLES)

31:21.630 --> 31:23.291
Good. Good.

31:28.262 --> 31:29.468
KING GEORGE VI: Though,

31:30.222 --> 31:34.215
probably wise to let the Princess Elizabeth

31:34.310 --> 31:36.972
undertake the Commonwealth tour, hmm?

31:37.063 --> 31:38.928
-(LIGHTER CLICKS)
-What say you?

31:39.982 --> 31:41.722
(STUTTERS) Is she up to it?

31:42.318 --> 31:44.229
Yes, I'd say so.

31:45.154 --> 31:47.861
(CLEARS THROAT AND GRUNTS) Besides,

31:47.948 --> 31:51.406
we have to start
breaking her in gently, don't we?

31:51.494 --> 31:52.529
Do we?

31:53.704 --> 31:55.740
Keep one eye on the future.

31:57.041 --> 31:58.827
The distant future.

32:04.340 --> 32:04.453
(APPLAUSE AND CLAMORING)

32:04.465 --> 32:06.421
(APPLAUSE AND CLAMORING)

32:38.707 --> 32:41.084
-MAN: Welcome back, sir.
-What's this?

32:41.168 --> 32:43.659
-MAN: It's the teleprinter.
-Let's have it upstairs.

32:43.754 --> 32:45.836
-Everything as it was before, sir?
-Yes!

32:45.923 --> 32:48.130
Everything exactly as it was before.

32:48.217 --> 32:50.208
Ladies. Ladies.

32:51.220 --> 32:52.801
Uh... Who's this?

32:54.390 --> 32:56.221
Oh, um, Miss Venetia Scott, sir.

32:56.725 --> 32:57.805
A new addition.

32:58.686 --> 33:01.428
-A good one, I'd say.
-JOCK: Thank you, sir.

33:03.482 --> 33:05.814
I had hoped I'd seen the back of this place.

33:06.694 --> 33:08.901
Could you give us a moment, please, Jock?

33:09.822 --> 33:10.902
Thank you.

33:13.242 --> 33:14.732
How is the King?

33:16.453 --> 33:21.618
He talked a great deal about his recovery.
Lots of mentions of "bouncing back."

33:22.751 --> 33:25.083
Which always makes one fear the worst.

33:25.754 --> 33:27.494
Not to mention the makeup.

33:30.843 --> 33:32.424
He was wearing rouge.

33:33.429 --> 33:34.760
Poor man.

33:38.434 --> 33:39.514
It's cancer.

33:42.605 --> 33:43.594
What?

33:47.735 --> 33:48.770
Who knows?

33:50.696 --> 33:51.902
No one.

33:53.115 --> 33:54.150
Least of all him.

33:54.617 --> 33:56.073
(KNOCKS AND OPENS DOOR)

33:56.160 --> 33:59.493
-Sir, lunch.
-Uh... Let's have it in here.

34:00.456 --> 34:03.994
See what they've been serving
for the past five years.

34:05.419 --> 34:06.750
CLEMMIE: So, he's dying?

34:07.254 --> 34:08.790
We're all dying.

34:10.007 --> 34:13.670
That's what defines the condition of living.

34:13.761 --> 34:16.002
Will he die tomorrow? No.

34:16.180 --> 34:19.764
What about the day after tomorrow?
And the day after that?

34:19.850 --> 34:22.307
The country needs to be led
by someone strong.

34:22.394 --> 34:24.055
Well, I'm strong.

34:24.146 --> 34:27.638
You are also tired, Winston. We both are.

34:28.817 --> 34:31.684
A situation like that
would require enormous energy.

34:33.322 --> 34:35.313
(SIGHS) And I won't lie to you.

34:35.407 --> 34:38.774
I have considered resigning
for Anthony's sake.

34:39.453 --> 34:40.818
Foryoursake.

34:41.247 --> 34:46.708
But then I realized a situation like that
would also require statesmanship.

34:46.794 --> 34:49.752
The party needs me. The country needs me.

34:49.838 --> 34:51.214
She needs me.

34:51.799 --> 34:52.834
Who?

34:53.509 --> 34:54.544
Her!

34:56.428 --> 34:57.508
-Oh, her.
-(MATCH STRIKES)

35:00.349 --> 35:03.261
PHILIP: This is Clarence House dining room
to Clarence House kitchen.

35:03.352 --> 35:04.717
Dining room to kitchen.

35:06.355 --> 35:09.597
-CHARLES: Dining room to kitchen.
-Yes. Dining room to kitchen.

35:09.775 --> 35:11.060
-(YELLS)
-Oh, bugger it.

35:14.446 --> 35:15.947
Right, I'm off.

35:16.865 --> 35:19.026
-Breakfast with your mother?
-And Margaret.

35:19.118 --> 35:22.702
Imagine. I'm checking curtain fabrics
in an hour.

35:23.998 --> 35:25.363
-(CHUCKLES)
-PHILIP: Yes.

35:28.836 --> 35:30.076
Let's pick the curtains.

35:31.005 --> 35:33.587
-Where to, ma'am?
-Buckingham Palace, please.

35:36.969 --> 35:38.300
Buckingham Palace.

35:46.312 --> 35:48.394
-| see.
-(KNOCK ON DOOR)

35:48.480 --> 35:50.095
MAN: The Queen has asked to see you.

35:50.899 --> 35:53.481
Yes, we look fonNard
to seeing the doctor then.

35:53.569 --> 35:56.151
-Thank you. Goodbye.
-Drawing room!

35:56.238 --> 35:58.024
-Now?
-Yes.

36:05.372 --> 36:07.988
We do both so love living at Clarence House,

36:08.083 --> 36:11.325
and he has all sorts of ideas
about how to modernize it.

36:11.420 --> 36:13.752
He really is
rather ingenious like that, actually.

36:13.839 --> 36:14.919
Now, Peter.

36:15.007 --> 36:16.998
PETER: Your Majesty.
Your Royal Highnesses.

36:17.092 --> 36:19.708
I have to make a decision about Christmas.

36:19.803 --> 36:23.421
Tell me, do you think the King
will be well enough to go to Sandringham?

36:23.807 --> 36:26.344
I do. As a matter of fact,
I think it would do him good.

36:27.269 --> 36:28.600
So, it's decided.

36:28.771 --> 36:30.352
Will you be joining us, too?

36:31.940 --> 36:32.929
Me?

36:34.193 --> 36:37.731
'Course not. Peter will be spending
Christmas at home with his family.

36:37.946 --> 36:40.198
I was only thinking of Papa.

36:40.449 --> 36:43.191
Given the choice,
you know he'd never let him out of his sight.

36:43.285 --> 36:44.616
QUEEN MOTHER: Well, that's true.

36:45.329 --> 36:46.785
He's quite devoted to you.

36:47.414 --> 36:49.154
Then let me discuss it with Rosemary.

36:49.583 --> 36:52.040
No. No, it's out of the question.

36:52.711 --> 36:53.996
Why, Mummy?

36:54.671 --> 36:56.457
Let Peter discuss it.

36:56.548 --> 36:57.537
(QUEEN MOTHER SIGHS)

36:59.551 --> 37:01.416
-Well, he did offer.
-QUEEN MOTHER: Very well.

37:01.512 --> 37:02.843
(BELL TRILLING)

37:02.930 --> 37:05.387
But as a wife,
I know what my answer would be.

37:05.474 --> 37:08.807
I'd want my husband at home
at Christmas with his children.

37:09.186 --> 37:10.517
Excuse me.

37:17.361 --> 37:18.350
(DOOR SHUTS)

37:23.617 --> 37:24.823
I saw that.

37:26.537 --> 37:29.074
What? No, I haven't finished.

37:30.165 --> 37:31.951
That look between the two of you.

37:35.003 --> 37:38.040
-Margaret.
-You must tell no one.

37:38.966 --> 37:42.174
The papers all think
I'm for Johnny Dalkeith or Billy Wallace.

37:42.302 --> 37:46.045
-Mummy and Papa, too, by the way.
-They're just boys, whereas Peter is...

37:46.140 --> 37:50.258
No, I quite see the attraction of Peter,
but he's married.

37:51.770 --> 37:52.759
(CUP CLINKING)

38:03.866 --> 38:04.901
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

38:04.992 --> 38:06.778
(DOOR OPENS)

38:08.787 --> 38:10.402
Dr. Weir, Your Majesty.

38:15.836 --> 38:16.825
(DOOR SHUTS)

38:18.213 --> 38:23.333
You told me that after the operation,
I might expect some

38:24.386 --> 38:25.592
soreness.

38:26.472 --> 38:30.215
Some difficulty breathing.

38:31.185 --> 38:35.178
But, um, you didn't tell me about this.

38:38.775 --> 38:40.731
-How often?
-All the time.

38:43.071 --> 38:49.442
At the time of the operation, as you know,
structural alterations were discovered.

38:49.536 --> 38:51.697
Of course. The blockage in the lung.

38:53.373 --> 38:56.115
It's time we gave that blockage a name, sir.

38:57.419 --> 38:58.875
It was a tumor.

38:59.630 --> 39:00.915
A malignant tumor.

39:08.555 --> 39:09.886
I see.

39:11.558 --> 39:12.718
(SIGHS)

39:13.101 --> 39:15.934
But we removed it.

39:16.355 --> 39:17.561
DR. WEIR: We did.

39:18.273 --> 39:19.934
So, what is this?

39:20.859 --> 39:24.101
We removed the left lung, sir, but the right

39:25.948 --> 39:30.863
has fewer, but still significant, blockages.

39:31.954 --> 39:33.069
(SIGHS)

39:41.838 --> 39:42.827
(SIGHS)

39:46.760 --> 39:48.045
So, what's next?

39:49.972 --> 39:51.087
Next?

39:54.059 --> 39:55.219
(SIGHS)

39:57.145 --> 40:00.888
I argued that His Majesty
should be told at the time.

40:01.483 --> 40:04.065
A patient has a right to know the full picture.

40:04.486 --> 40:06.192
But I was overruled.

40:06.363 --> 40:08.854
The theory was that
if His Majesty felt he'd been cured,

40:09.074 --> 40:13.568
he could throw himself into his work
without undue stress and worry.

40:31.722 --> 40:33.883
I have two questions.

40:36.101 --> 40:38.057
Who knows the full picture?

40:39.813 --> 40:41.553
Apart from the surgeons,

40:42.566 --> 40:45.023
perhaps the Prime Minister, sir.

40:50.198 --> 40:51.358
Of course.

40:54.661 --> 40:56.617
But not the Queen?

40:58.415 --> 41:01.748
-Nor anyone else in my family?
-No, sir.

41:08.091 --> 41:09.877
And the second question?

41:15.682 --> 41:17.593
It's impossible to say, sir.

41:18.935 --> 41:22.723
My understanding is the surgeons
did everything they could.

41:26.109 --> 41:27.315
And?

41:29.613 --> 41:31.194
It could be years.

41:31.740 --> 41:32.855
(SIGHS)

41:32.949 --> 41:35.281
More likely months.

41:38.955 --> 41:40.240
Thank you.

41:44.795 --> 41:46.751
(TRAIN WHISTLING)

42:11.613 --> 42:13.774
(CLAMORING)

42:27.087 --> 42:29.203
(MUFFLED CLAMORING)

42:40.642 --> 42:42.678
-(HORN HONKING)
-(CLAMORING)

43:00.996 --> 43:05.956
In the bleak midwinter

43:06.209 --> 43:11.124
Frosty wind made moan

43:11.339 --> 43:16.550
In the bleak midwinter...

43:18.346 --> 43:19.506
Merry Christmas.

43:24.770 --> 43:27.853
...archangels

43:28.231 --> 43:32.645
May have gathered there

43:32.944 --> 43:33.979
Come on.

43:34.196 --> 43:39.190
Cherubim and seraphim

43:39.409 --> 43:43.448
Thronged the air

43:43.830 --> 43:48.950
But His mother only

43:49.044 --> 43:53.708
In her maiden bliss

43:54.716 --> 43:59.710
Worshipped the beloved

44:00.138 --> 44:04.928
With a kiss

44:07.312 --> 44:08.552
Oh, look.

44:20.575 --> 44:21.610
(CHUCKLES)

44:23.870 --> 44:25.485
(ALL CHATTERING AND LAUGHING)

44:25.580 --> 44:27.445
Charming. Quite charming.

44:34.589 --> 44:39.208
What can / give Him

44:39.302 --> 44:43.045
Poor as / am?

44:46.017 --> 44:50.351
If / were a shepherd

44:51.106 --> 44:55.440
/ would bring a lamb

44:56.570 --> 45:01.781
If / were a wise man

45:02.325 --> 45:07.160
/ would do my part

45:07.998 --> 45:14.119
Yet what / can / give him?

45:14.796 --> 45:21.292
Give my heart

45:32.314 --> 45:34.475
(CLAPS)

45:42.991 --> 45:44.197
Thank you.

45:46.161 --> 45:48.368
Thank you. Thank you.

45:48.663 --> 45:50.494
-(BELL RINGS)
-(LAUGHING)

45:54.669 --> 45:57.001
Very good. Charles, come on.

45:58.214 --> 45:59.795
-All right.
-No, Mummy.

46:00.800 --> 46:04.008
Ma'am, His Majesty has requested
you attend him in his study.

46:05.263 --> 46:07.299
Urgently requested, ma'am.

46:08.975 --> 46:10.010
All right.

46:11.102 --> 46:12.763
Will you take them?

46:12.854 --> 46:14.390
I'll be back soon.

46:17.317 --> 46:19.524
WOMAN: All right. Off we go then.

46:27.911 --> 46:32.496
In case you're wondering,
I haven't anything specific to say.

46:33.458 --> 46:35.870
Just wanted to spend time with you.

46:37.754 --> 46:38.869
(CHUCKLES)

46:43.510 --> 46:46.718
If there's anything you wanted to ask me,
just fire away.

46:50.225 --> 46:51.556
Are they a nuisance?

46:52.978 --> 46:54.343
The boxes.

46:54.771 --> 46:56.932
Not if you keep on top of them.

46:58.233 --> 47:01.225
-Even at Christmas?
-Even at Christmas.

47:03.196 --> 47:04.652
Well, what's inside?

47:05.198 --> 47:08.782
Everything they want me to know,
they stick on top.

47:09.035 --> 47:11.492
Everything they'd rather I didn't know,

47:11.579 --> 47:15.071
Cabinet meetings, Foreign Office briefings,

47:15.166 --> 47:17.657
they tuck away at the bottom.

47:17.752 --> 47:19.367
Which is why

47:20.463 --> 47:23.955
the first thing I do
when no one is looking is this.

47:24.134 --> 47:25.123
(CLANGS)

47:26.219 --> 47:28.050
(LAUGHING AND COUGHING)

47:28.138 --> 47:29.127
(BOTH LAUGH)

47:29.222 --> 47:30.587
(COUGHING)

47:32.100 --> 47:34.216
(COUGHING) Will you take that? Thank you.

47:34.978 --> 47:37.094
(COUGHING INTENSIFIES)

47:42.360 --> 47:44.442
Oh. (CLEARS THROAT)

47:44.988 --> 47:47.024
(GASPING)

47:48.658 --> 47:49.818
Yeah.

47:50.243 --> 47:51.232
(LOCK CLICKS)

47:52.787 --> 47:55.449
(SIGHS)

48:08.720 --> 48:10.130
Don't you get sick of it all?

48:12.307 --> 48:14.172
(SIGHS) I do.

48:14.934 --> 48:15.969
And lonely?

48:19.856 --> 48:21.141
Sometimes.

48:22.609 --> 48:26.443
Which is why it's so important
to have the right person by your side.

48:27.906 --> 48:30.818
I've been very lucky
in that regard with your mother.

48:33.828 --> 48:34.943
How's your fellow?

48:35.705 --> 48:36.911
-Philip?
-Hmm.

48:39.584 --> 48:40.824
Well, he...

48:42.837 --> 48:46.500
Well, I'm afraid he's become
something of a snagaholic.

48:46.841 --> 48:48.422
-(CHUCKLES)
-A what?

48:48.676 --> 48:50.507
Well, you know we're renovating
Clarence House

48:50.595 --> 48:52.176
to make it our permanent home?

48:53.014 --> 48:54.094
Mmm-hmm. Yes.

48:54.182 --> 48:57.094
Well, ever since he started
supervising the work,

48:57.185 --> 49:00.268
he can't look at anything
without seeing its faults.

49:00.355 --> 49:04.724
"That switch is an inch too high.
And that door handle's wrong."

49:05.401 --> 49:08.017
"Well, don't be silly," I say.
"A handle's a handle."

49:08.530 --> 49:10.236
I should make more of an effort with him.

49:12.617 --> 49:13.823
Take him shooting.

49:14.285 --> 49:16.947
-Would he like that?
-Yes, I think he'd love it.

49:17.038 --> 49:19.871
And then when your health's improved,
we'll return to Malta,

49:20.125 --> 49:23.458
and he'll have his navy again,
and all will be well.

49:23.545 --> 49:24.876
Of course.

49:26.047 --> 49:28.208
But, uh, in the meantime,

49:32.470 --> 49:35.007
Not long distances, anyway.

49:35.932 --> 49:39.720
Which brings me to the
forthcoming Commonwealth tour.

49:39.894 --> 49:44.263
I was wondering if you would consider
stepping into my shoes, so to speak.

49:45.567 --> 49:51.153
My health is improving,
but I'm still not yet well enough.

49:52.073 --> 49:54.564
Well, if you think we're up to it.

49:55.201 --> 49:56.316
You'll be fine.

49:58.037 --> 49:59.117
Where is it?

49:59.914 --> 50:01.029
Well...

50:01.291 --> 50:03.282
Ceylon, Australia,

50:04.043 --> 50:06.625
then on to New Zealand, Bermuda.

50:06.713 --> 50:09.204
And there's talk of starting in Kenya.

50:09.299 --> 50:10.835
Very good.

50:10.925 --> 50:12.836
Right, we'll be gone months.

50:13.052 --> 50:14.087
(QUEEN MOTHER LAUGHS)

50:14.512 --> 50:15.627
Yes.

50:16.097 --> 50:18.088
But it would mean so much to Papa
that we do it.

50:18.308 --> 50:19.764
And what am I supposed to do all that time?

50:19.934 --> 50:21.890
Don't worry, we'll put you to work.

50:23.188 --> 50:25.144
My work is as a naval officer,

50:25.231 --> 50:26.607
not grinning like a demented ape

50:26.691 --> 50:28.147
-while you cut ribbons.
-Shh!

50:28.234 --> 50:31.726
-What about the children?
-The children will be fine.

50:31.821 --> 50:34.938
Without their parents for months on end?

50:35.617 --> 50:39.030
-Daddy, can you come and play?
-I won't be a moment, darling.

50:39.120 --> 50:42.203
If you go and play with Grandpapa,
I'll be right over. Good boy.

50:42.290 --> 50:44.531
QUEEN MOTHER: Come on, darling,
Daddy's busy. Come and start again.

50:44.626 --> 50:46.537
-CHARLES: Daddy's coming.
-They won't know.

50:47.629 --> 50:49.995
-They're too young to notice.
-ANNE: Come on. Be quiet.

50:50.089 --> 50:52.125
It would so help in Papa's recovery.

50:54.886 --> 50:56.376
KING GEORGE VI: Charles, come back here.

50:57.096 --> 51:00.384
CHARLES: Daddy, can you play now?
KING GEORGE VI: Charles.

51:06.439 --> 51:07.474
Yes.

51:09.484 --> 51:11.224
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

51:11.444 --> 51:12.559
Thank you.

51:12.737 --> 51:14.693
PHILIP: What are we playing?
CHARLES: Granny's footsteps.

51:14.989 --> 51:17.856
PHILIP: All right. Come on then. Let's go.
And then it's bedtime.

51:18.117 --> 51:20.244
QUEEN MOTHER: Ready, steady...

51:20.453 --> 51:22.489
(BAGPIPES PLAYING)

51:28.336 --> 51:30.452
(WHEEZING COUGHS)

51:42.517 --> 51:43.506
Sir?

51:51.442 --> 51:52.431
(SNIFFLES)

51:56.030 --> 51:57.861
What's the weather like today?

51:58.658 --> 52:00.694
Rather misty at the moment, sir.

52:02.495 --> 52:03.860
KING GEORGE VI: Morning!

52:04.080 --> 52:05.069
(MUMBLES)

52:05.206 --> 52:06.412
PHILIP: Bugger off.

52:07.709 --> 52:12.043
Yes, I'm not sure that's the correct address
for the King of England.

52:13.548 --> 52:16.335
-It's a beautiful morning for duck.
-What?

52:16.426 --> 52:18.917
I thought Wolferton Splash.

52:25.143 --> 52:26.178
Christ.

52:30.231 --> 52:32.187
(COUGHS)

52:34.527 --> 52:36.438
KING GEORGE VI: Reed warbler, see?

52:38.448 --> 52:41.281
Oh, teal. Below the withy there.

52:42.744 --> 52:47.033
When Iwoke up this morning, I thought
we'd go to Babingley Flat or Eleven Acres.

52:47.123 --> 52:50.160
But in the end... (CLEARS THROAT)
...there's nowhere better than the Splash

52:50.251 --> 52:53.493
with a bagful of cartridges to lift the spirits.

52:53.588 --> 52:55.624
His Majesty's back to himself again.

52:55.715 --> 52:58.798
He is, thank you. Like a young man again.

52:59.010 --> 53:00.671
(COUGHS)

53:05.099 --> 53:06.214
(GRUNTS)

53:06.309 --> 53:07.765
(CHUCKLES)

53:07.852 --> 53:10.218
We'll be all right.
My son-in-Iaw's a naval man.

53:10.480 --> 53:13.847
We will. If I can handle a frigate.

53:13.941 --> 53:14.976
(COUGHING)

53:30.500 --> 53:32.991
You understand the titles,

53:34.629 --> 53:35.869
the dukedom,

53:37.507 --> 53:40.169
-they're not the job.
-Sir?

53:44.013 --> 53:45.924
She is the job.

53:47.767 --> 53:51.225
She is the essence of your duty.

53:52.647 --> 53:54.137
Loving her.

53:55.775 --> 53:57.561
Protecting her.

54:01.656 --> 54:03.647
Of course you'll miss your career.

54:06.494 --> 54:10.282
But doing this for her, doing this for me,

54:14.001 --> 54:16.959
there'll be no greater act of patriotism

54:19.006 --> 54:20.041
or love.

54:25.096 --> 54:26.677
I understand, sir.

54:29.350 --> 54:30.715
Do you, boy?

54:32.353 --> 54:34.014
Do you really?

54:39.485 --> 54:40.895
I think so.

54:51.873 --> 54:56.333
Now, let's go shoot some duck, shall we?

54:56.419 --> 54:58.159
Three cheers for His Majesty!

54:58.254 --> 55:00.085
-Hip, hip...
-ALL: Hooray!

55:00.173 --> 55:02.380
-Hip, hip...
-ALL: Hooray!

55:02.467 --> 55:04.332
-Hip, hip...
-ALL: Hooray!

55:04.427 --> 55:06.383
You're too kind. Thank you.

